# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cereal-germ
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cereal-germ/abb-grain] ABB traced its origins to the former Australian Barley Board.
[src:cereal-germ/abb-grain] Due to the company's expanded operations into different areas, it demutualised to become ABB Grain on 1 July 1999.
[src:cereal-germ/abb-grain] In 2004, the company merged with the South Australian storage and handling company AusBulk and United Grower Holdings.
[src:cereal-germ/abb-grain] This brought about the control of the two major grain handlers, along with several of AusBulk's divisions.
[src:cereal-germ/abb-grain] The company also provided rural services including fertiliser and agrichemical supply and wool and livestock activities.
[src:cereal-germ/abb-grain] The latter were supported by the acquisitions of the Adelaide Wool Company, Wardle Co and Stawool in 2007.
[src:cereal-germ/abb-grain] ABB had significant operations in New Zealand focused on the trading and distribution of grains and proteins.
[src:cereal-germ/abb-grain] In 2007, the company established a joint venture in Ukraine with French malting company Soufflet to accumulate grain, manage supply chain activities and market grain.
[src:cereal-germ/abb-grain] In April 2009, Viterra launched a takeover offer.
[src:cereal-germ/abb-grain] Combined, the two companies together were responsible for 37 per cent of the world's exports of wheat, canola and barley.
[src:cereal-germ/abb-grain] Shareholders approved the merger on 9 September.
[src:cereal-germ/abb-grain] ABB was delisted from the Australian Securities Exchange on 25 September 2009.
[src:cereal-germ/agronomy] This topic of agronomy involves selective breeding of plants to produce the best crops for various conditions.
[src:cereal-germ/agronomy] Plant breeding has increased crop yields and has improved the nutritional value of numerous crops, including corn, soybeans, and wheat.
[src:cereal-germ/agronomy] It has also resulted in the development of new types of plants.
[src:cereal-germ/agronomy] For example, a hybrid grain named triticale was produced by crossbreeding rye and wheat.
[src:cereal-germ/agronomy] Triticale contains more usable protein than does either rye or wheat.
[src:cereal-germ/agronomy] Agronomy has also been instrumental for fruit and vegetable production research.
[src:cereal-germ/agronomy] Furthermore, the application of plant breeding for turfgrass development has resulted in a reduction in the demand for fertilizer and water inputs (requirements), as well as turf-types with higher disease resistance.
[src:cereal-germ/agronomy] Agronomists use biotechnology to extend and expedite the development of desired characteristics.
[src:cereal-germ/agronomy] Biotechnology is often a laboratory activity requiring field testing of new crop varieties that are developed.
[src:cereal-germ/agronomy] In addition to increasing crop yields agronomic biotechnology is being applied increasingly for novel uses other than food.
[src:cereal-germ/agronomy] For example, oilseed is at present used mainly for margarine and other food oils, but it can be modified to produce fatty acids for detergents, substitute fuels and petrochemicals.
[src:cereal-germ/agronomy] Agronomists study sustainable ways to make soils more productive and profitable.
[src:cereal-germ/agronomy] They classify soils and analyze them to determine whether they contain nutrients vital for plant growth.
[src:cereal-germ/agronomy] Common macronutrients analyzed include compounds of nitrogen, phosphorus, potassium, calcium, magnesium, and sulfur.
[src:cereal-germ/agronomy] Soil is also assessed for several micronutrients, like zinc and boron.
[src:cereal-germ/agronomy] The percentage of organic matter, soil pH, and nutrient holding capacity (cation exchange capacity) are tested in a regional laboratory.
[src:cereal-germ/agronomy] Agronomists will interpret these laboratory reports and make recommendations to modify soil nutrients for optimal plant growth.
[src:cereal-germ/agronomy] Additionally, agronomists develop methods to preserve soil and decrease the effects of [erosion] by wind and water.
[src:cereal-germ/agronomy] For example, a technique known as contour plowing may be used to prevent soil erosion and conserve rainfall.
[src:cereal-germ/agronomy] Researchers of agronomy also seek ways to use the soil more effectively for solving other problems.
[src:cereal-germ/agronomy] Such problems include the disposal of human and animal manure, water pollution, and pesticide accumulation in the soil, as well as preserving the soil for future generations such as the burning of paddocks after crop production.
[src:cereal-germ/agronomy] Pasture management techniques include no-till farming, planting of soil-binding grasses along contours on steep slopes, and using contour drains of depths as much as 1 metre.
[src:cereal-germ/agronomy] Agroecology is the management of agricultural systems with an emphasis on ecological and environmental applications.
[src:cereal-germ/agronomy] This topic is associated closely with work for sustainable agriculture, organic farming, and alternative food systems and the development of alternative cropping systems.
[src:cereal-germ/agronomy] Theoretical production ecology is the quantitative study of the growth of crops.
[src:cereal-germ/agronomy] The plant is treated as a kind of biological factory, which processes light, carbon dioxide, water, and nutrients into harvestable products.
[src:cereal-germ/agronomy] The main parameters are temperature, sunlight, standing crop biomass, plant production distribution, and nutrient and water supply.
[src:cereal-germ/alfred-a-knopf] The Knopf publishing house is associated with the borzoi logo in its colophon, which was designed by co-founder Blanche Knopf in 1925.
[src:cereal-germ/alfred-a-knopf] Knopf Sr. along with Blanche Knopf, on a $5,000 advance from his father, Samuel Knopf.
[src:cereal-germ/alfred-a-knopf] The first office was located in New York's Candler Building.
[src:cereal-germ/alfred-a-knopf] The publishing house was officially incorporated in 1918, with Alfred Knopf as president, Blanche Knopf as vice president, and Samuel Knopf as treasurer.
[src:cereal-germ/alfred-a-knopf] From the start, Knopf focused on European translations and high-brow works of literature.
[src:cereal-germ/alfred-a-knopf] Among their initial publications were French author Émile Augier's *Four Plays*, Russian writer Nikolai Gogol's *Taras Bulba*, Polish novelist Stanisław Przybyszewski's novel *Homo Sapiens*, and French writer Guy de Maupassant's *Yvette, a Novelette, and Ten Other Stories*.
[src:cereal-germ/alfred-a-knopf] During World War I these books were cheap to obtain and helped establish Knopf as an American firm publishing European works.
[src:cereal-germ/alfred-a-knopf] Their first bestseller was a new edition of *Green Mansions*, a novel by W.
[src:cereal-germ/alfred-a-knopf] Hudson which went through nine printings by 1919 and sold over 20,000 copies.
[src:cereal-germ/alfred-a-knopf] Their first original American novel, *The Three Black Pennys* by Joseph Hergesheimer, was published in 1917.
[src:cereal-germ/alfred-a-knopf] With the start of the 1920s Knopf began using innovative advertising techniques to draw attention to their books and authors.
[src:cereal-germ/alfred-a-knopf] Beginning in 1920, Knopf produced a chapbook for the purpose of promoting new books.
[src:cereal-germ/alfred-a-knopf] *The Borzoi* was published periodically over the years, the first being a hardback called *The Borzoi* and sometimes quarterly as *The Borzoi Quarterly*.
[src:cereal-germ/alfred-a-knopf] For Floyd Dell's coming-of-age novel, *Moon-Calf*, they paid men to walk the streets of the financial and theatre districts dressed in artist costumes with sandwich boards.
[src:cereal-germ/alfred-a-knopf] The placards had a copy of the book for browsing and directed interested buyers to local book shops.
[src:cereal-germ/alfred-a-knopf] The unique look of their books along with their expertise in advertising their authors drew Willa Cather to leave her previous publisher Houghton Mifflin to join Alfred A.
[src:cereal-germ/alfred-a-knopf] As she was still under contract for her novels, the Knopfs suggested publishing a collection of her short stories, *Youth and the Bright Medusa*, in 1920.
[src:cereal-germ/alfred-a-knopf] Cather was pleased with the results and the advertisement of the book in *The New Republic* and would go on to publish sixteen books with Knopf, including their first Pulitzer Prize winner, *One of Ours*.
[src:cereal-germ/alfred-a-knopf] Before they had married, Alfred had promised Blanche that they would be equal partners in the publishing company, but it was clear by the company's fifth anniversary that this was not to be the case.
[src:cereal-germ/alfred-a-knopf] Knopf published a celebratory fifth-anniversary book in which Alfred was the focus of anecdotes by authors and Blanche's name was only mentioned once to note that "Mrs.
[src:cereal-germ/alfred-a-knopf] This despite ample evidence from authors and others that Blanche was in fact the soul of the company.
[src:cereal-germ/alfred-a-knopf] This was covered extensively in *The Lady with the Borzoi* by Laura Claridge.
[src:cereal-germ/alfred-a-knopf] In 1923, Knopf also started publishing periodicals, beginning with *The American Mercury*, founded by H.
[src:cereal-germ/alfred-a-knopf] Mencken and George Jean Nathan, which it published through 1934.
[src:cereal-germ/alfred-a-knopf] Also in 1923, Knopf published Kahlil Gibran's *The Prophet*.
[src:cereal-germ/alfred-a-knopf] Knopf had published Gibran's earlier works which had disappointing sales.
[src:cereal-germ/alfred-a-knopf] In its first year, *The Prophet* only sold 1,159 copies.
[src:cereal-germ/alfred-a-knopf] It would double sales the next year and keep doubling becoming one of the firm's most successful books.
[src:cereal-germ/alfred-a-knopf] Approaching its 100 year anniversary in 2023, *The Prophet* has been translated into over 100 languages and has never gone out of print for Knopf.
[src:cereal-germ/alfred-a-knopf] In the 1920s, Knopf sometimes withdrew or censored their books when threatened by John Sumner, such as Floyd Dell's *Janet March* or George Egerton's 1899 translation of *Hunger*.
[src:cereal-germ/alfred-a-knopf] Koshland joined the company in 1934, and worked with the firm for more than fifty years, rising to take the positions of president and chairman of the board.
[src:cereal-germ/alfred-a-knopf] Blanche became president in 1957 when Alfred became chairman of the board, and worked steadily for the firm until her death in 1966.
[src:cereal-germ/alfred-a-knopf] Alfred Knopf retired in 1972, becoming chairman emeritus of the firm until his death in 1984.
[src:cereal-germ/alfred-a-knopf] Alfred Knopf also had a summer home in Purchase, New York.
[src:cereal-germ/alfred-a-knopf] Following the Good Neighbor policy, Blanche Knopf visited South America in 1942, so the firm could start producing texts from there.
[src:cereal-germ/alfred-a-knopf] She was one of the first publishers to visit Europe after World War II.
[src:cereal-germ/alfred-a-knopf] Her trips, and those of other editors, brought in new writers from Europe, South America, and Asia.
[src:cereal-germ/alfred-a-knopf] Alfred traveled to Brazil in 1961, which spurred a corresponding interest on his part in South America.
[src:cereal-germ/alfred-a-knopf] Penn Publishing Company was acquired in 1943.
[src:cereal-germ/alfred-a-knopf] The Knopfs' son, Alfred "Pat" Jr., was hired on as secretary and trade books manager after the war.
[src:cereal-germ/alfred-a-knopf] In 1957, editor Judith Jones joined Knopf.
[src:cereal-germ/alfred-a-knopf] Jones, who had discovered *Anne Frank: Diary of a Young Girl* while working at Doubleday, acquired Simone Beck, Louisette Bertholle and Julia Child's *Mastering the Art of French Cooking* for Knopf.
[src:cereal-germ/alfred-a-knopf] Jones would remain with Knopf, retiring in 2011 as a senior editor and vice-president after a career that included working with John Updike and Anne Tyler.
[src:cereal-germ/alfred-a-knopf] Pat Knopf left his parents' publishing company in 1959 to launch his own, Atheneum Publishers, with two other partners.
[src:cereal-germ/alfred-a-knopf] The story made the front page of *The New York Times*.
[src:cereal-germ/alfred-a-knopf] In a 1957 advertisement in *The Atlantic Monthly*, Alfred A.
[src:cereal-germ/alfred-a-knopf] The credo includes a list of what Knopf's beliefs for publishing including the statement that he never published an unworthy book.
[src:cereal-germ/alfred-a-knopf] In 1960, Random House acquired Alfred A.
[src:cereal-germ/alfred-a-knopf] It is believed that the decision to sell was prompted by Alfred A.
[src:cereal-germ/alfred-a-knopf] Knopf Jr., leaving Knopf to found his own book company, Atheneum Books, in 1959.
[src:cereal-germ/alfred-a-knopf] Since its founding, Knopf has paid close attention to design and typography, employing notable designers and typographers including William Addison Dwiggins, Harry Ford, Steven Heller, Chip Kidd, Lorraine Louie, Peter Mendelsund, Bruce Rogers, Rudolf Ruzicka, and Beatrice Warde.
[src:cereal-germ/alfred-a-knopf] Knopf books conclude with an unnumbered page titled "A Note on the Type", which describes the history of the typeface used for the book.
[src:cereal-germ/alfred-a-knopf] In addition, Knopf books date the year of the book's current printing on the title page.
[src:cereal-germ/alfred-a-knopf] Knopf published textbooks until 1988, when Random House's schools and colleges division was sold to McGraw Hill.
[src:cereal-germ/alfred-a-knopf] In 1991, Knopf revived the "Everyman's Library" series, originally published in England in the early 20th century.
[src:cereal-germ/alfred-a-knopf] This series consists of classics of world literature in affordable hardcover editions.
[src:cereal-germ/alfred-a-knopf] The series has grown over the years to include lines of *Children's Classics* and *Pocket Poets*.
[src:cereal-germ/alfred-a-knopf] Random House was acquired by Bertelsmann AG in 1998.
[src:cereal-germ/alfred-a-knopf] In late 2008 and early 2009, the Knopf Publishing Group merged with Doubleday to form the Knopf Doubleday Publishing Group.
[src:cereal-germ/alfred-a-knopf] Random House has been owned since its 2013 merger of Penguin Group by Penguin Random House, a joint venture between Bertelsmann (53%) and Pearson PLC (47%).
[src:cereal-germ/alfred-a-knopf] Many of Knopf's hardcover books are published later as Vintage paperbacks.
[src:cereal-germ/alfred-a-knopf] Vintage Books is a sister imprint of Random House.
[src:cereal-germ/alfred-a-knopf] In October 2012, Bertelsmann entered into talks with rival conglomerate Pearson plc, over the possibility of combining their respective publishing companies, Random House and Penguin Group.
[src:cereal-germ/alfred-a-knopf] The merger was completed on 1 July 2013 and the new company is Penguin Random House.
[src:cereal-germ/alfred-a-knopf] Bertelsmann owned 53% of the joint venture while Pearson owned 47%.
[src:cereal-germ/alfred-a-knopf] At the time of the acquisition the combined companies controlled 25% of the book business, with more than 10,000 employees and 250 independent publishing imprints and with about $3.9 billion in annual revenues.
[src:cereal-germ/alfred-a-knopf] The move to consolidate was to provide leverage against Amazon.com and battle the shrinking state of bookstores.
[src:cereal-germ/alfred-a-knopf] In 2015, Knopf celebrated its 100th anniversary by publishing a commemorative book, *Alfred A.
[src:cereal-germ/alfred-a-knopf] While there have been many notable editors at Knopf there have only been four editors-in-chief: Alfred A.
[src:cereal-germ/alfred-a-knopf] Knopf, Sr., Robert Gottlieb, Sonny Mehta (who died in 2019) and Jordan Pavlin.
[src:cereal-germ/alfred-a-knopf] Knopf also employed literary scouts to good advantage.
[src:cereal-germ/alfred-a-knopf] Hamilton, Kazuo Ishiguro, John Keegan, Nella Larsen, John le Carré, Jack London, Gabriel García Márquez, Cormac McCarthy, Toni Morrison, Alice Munro, Haruki Murakami, Cynthia Ozick, Christopher Paolini, Edgar Allan Poe, Ezra Pound, Anne Rice, Dorothy Richardson, Stephen M.
[src:cereal-germ/alfred-a-knopf] Silverman, Oswald Spengler, Susan Swan, Donna Tartt, Barbara W.
[src:cereal-germ/alfred-a-knopf] Tuchman, Anne Tyler, John Updike, Andrew Vachss, James D.
[src:cereal-germ/alfred-a-knopf] The logo for Knopf is a Russian wolfhound or Borzoi.
[src:cereal-germ/alfred-a-knopf] Blanche Knopf suggested the Borzoi for the logo to imply motion and the logo was used on both the spine and the title page of their books.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] These symptoms typically start in minutes to hours and then increase very rapidly to life-threatening levels.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Urgent medical treatment is required to prevent serious harm and death, even if the patient has used an epinephrine autoinjector or has taken other medications in response, and even if symptoms appear to be improving.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Common causes include allergies to insect bites and stings, allergies to foods—including nuts, peanuts, milk, fish, eggs; allergies to medications – including some antibiotics and non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs); or allergies to anaesthetics or latex.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Other causes can include physical exercise, and cases may also occur in some people due to escalating reactions to simple throat irritation or may also occur without an obvious reason.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] The mast cell disease mastocytosis, along with the mast cell disorder mast cell activation syndrome are both capable of triggering anaphylaxis.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] The mechanism involves the release of inflammatory mediators in a rapidly escalating cascade from certain types of white blood cells triggered by either immunologic or non-immunologic mechanisms.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Diagnosis is based on the presenting symptoms and signs after exposure to a potential allergen or irritant.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] The primary treatment of anaphylaxis is epinephrine injection into a muscle, intravenous fluids, then placing the person in a reclining position with feet elevated to help restore normal blood flow.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Additional doses of epinephrine may be required.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Other measures, such as antihistamines and steroids, are complementary.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Carrying an epinephrine autoinjector, commonly called an "epipen", and identification regarding the condition is recommended in people with a history of anaphylaxis.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Immediately contacting ambulance / EMT services is strongly recommended, regardless of any on-site treatment.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Getting to a doctor or hospital as soon as possible is important, even if the condition appears to be getting better.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Worldwide, 0.05–2% of the population is estimated to experience anaphylaxis at some point in life.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Globally, as underreporting declined into the 2010s, the rate appeared to be increasing.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] It occurs most often in young people and females.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] About 99.7% of people hospitalized with anaphylaxis in the United States survive.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] The word is derived from Ancient Greek: ἀνά, romanized: *ana*, lit.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] 'up', and Ancient Greek: φύλαξις, romanized: *phylaxis*, lit.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Anaphylaxis typically presents many different symptoms over minutes or hours with an average onset of 5 to 30 minutes if exposure is intravenous and up to 2 hours if from eating food.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] The most common areas affected include: skin (80–90%), respiratory (70%), gastrointestinal (30–45%), heart and vasculature (10–45%), and central nervous system (10–15%) with usually two or more being involved.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Symptoms typically include generalized hives, itchiness, flushing, or swelling (angioedema) of the affected tissues.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Those with angioedema may describe a burning sensation of the skin rather than itchiness.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Swelling of the tongue or throat occurs in up to about 20% of cases.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Other features may include a runny nose and swelling of the conjunctiva.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] The skin may also be blue tinged because of a lack of oxygen.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Respiratory symptoms and signs that may be present include shortness of breath, wheezes, or stridor.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] The wheezing is typically caused by spasms of the bronchial muscles while stridor is related to upper airway obstruction secondary to swelling.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Hoarseness, pain with swallowing, or a cough may also occur.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] While a fast heart rate caused by low blood pressure is more common, a Bezold–Jarisch reflex has been described in 10% of people, where a slow heart rate is associated with low blood pressure.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] A drop in blood pressure or shock (either distributive or cardiogenic) may cause the feeling of lightheadedness or loss of consciousness.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] In rare cases, very low blood pressure may be the only sign of anaphylaxis.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Coronary artery spasm may occur with subsequent myocardial infarction, dysrhythmia, or cardiac arrest.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Those with underlying coronary disease are at greater risk of cardiac effects from anaphylaxis.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] The coronary spasm is related to the presence of histamine-releasing cells in the heart.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Gastrointestinal symptoms may include severe crampy abdominal pain and vomiting.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] There may be confusion, a loss of bladder control or pelvic pain similar to that of uterine cramps.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Dilation of blood vessels around the brain may cause headaches.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] A feeling of anxiety or of "impending doom" has also been described.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Anaphylaxis can occur in response to almost any foreign substance.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Common triggers include venom from insect bites or stings, foods, and medication.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Foods are the most common trigger in children and young adults, while medications and insect bites and stings are more common in older adults.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Less common causes include: physical factors, biological agents such as semen, latex, hormonal changes, food additives and colors, and topical medications.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Physical factors such as exercise (known as exercise-induced anaphylaxis) or temperature (either hot or cold) may also act as triggers through their direct effects on mast cells.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Events caused by exercise are frequently associated with cofactors such as the ingestion of certain foods or taking an NSAID.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Anaphylaxis caused by a combination of exercise and consumption of certain foods is known as food-dependent exercise-induced anaphylaxis (FDEIA).
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] In aspirin-exacerbated respiratory disease (AERD), alcohol is a common trigger.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] During anesthesia, neuromuscular blocking agents, antibiotics, and latex are the most common causes.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] The cause remains unknown in 32–50% of cases, referred to as "idiopathic anaphylaxis." Six vaccines (MMR, varicella, influenza, hepatitis B, tetanus, meningococcal) are recognized as a cause for anaphylaxis, and HPV may cause anaphylaxis as well.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Many foods can trigger anaphylaxis; this may occur upon the first known ingestion.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Common triggering foods vary around the world due to cultural cuisine.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] In Western cultures, ingestion of or exposure to peanuts, wheat, nuts, certain types of seafood like shellfish, milk, fruit and eggs are the most prevalent causes.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Sesame is common in the Middle East, while rice and chickpeas are frequently encountered as sources of anaphylaxis in Asia.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Severe cases are usually caused by ingesting the allergen, but some people experience a severe reaction upon contact.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] By age 16, 80% of children with anaphylaxis to milk or eggs and 20% who experience isolated anaphylaxis to peanuts can tolerate these foods.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Any type of alcohol, even in small amounts, can trigger anaphylaxis in people with AERD.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Any medication may potentially trigger anaphylaxis.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] The most common are β-lactam antibiotics (such as penicillin) followed by aspirin and NSAIDs.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Other antibiotics are implicated less frequently.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Anaphylactic reactions to NSAIDs are either agent specific or occur among those that are structurally similar, meaning that those who are allergic to one NSAID can typically tolerate a different one or a different group of NSAIDs.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Other relatively common causes include chemotherapy, vaccines, protamine and herbal preparations.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Some medications (vancomycin, morphine, x-ray contrast among others) cause anaphylaxis by directly triggering mast cell degranulation.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] The frequency of a reaction to an agent partly depends on the frequency of its use and partly on its intrinsic properties.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Anaphylaxis to penicillin or cephalosporins occurs only after it binds to proteins inside the body with some agents binding more easily than others.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Anaphylaxis to penicillin occurs once in every 2,000 to 10,000 courses of treatment, with death occurring in fewer than one in every 50,000 courses of treatment.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Anaphylaxis to aspirin and NSAIDs occurs in about one in every 50,000 persons.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] If someone reacts to penicillin, his or her risk of a reaction to cephalosporins is greater but still less than one in 1,000.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] The old radiocontrast agents caused reactions in 1% of cases, while the newer, lower osmolar agents cause reactions in 0.04% of cases.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Avoidance of cephalosporins in those with penicillin allergy creates a significantly greater patient safety risk than the low probability of anaphylaxis.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Venom from stinging or biting insects such as Hymenoptera (ants, bees, and wasps) or Triatominae (kissing bugs) may cause anaphylaxis in susceptible people.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Previous reactions that are anything more than a local reaction around the site of the sting, are a risk factor for future anaphylaxis; however, half of the fatalities have had no previous systemic reaction.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] People with atopic diseases such as asthma, eczema, or allergic rhinitis are at high risk of anaphylaxis from food, latex, and radiocontrast agents but not from injectable medications or stings.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] One study in children found that 60% had a history of previous atopic diseases, and of children who die from anaphylaxis, more than 90% have asthma.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Those with mastocytosis, mast cell activation syndrome (MCAS) or of a higher socioeconomic status are at increased risk.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Anaphylaxis is a severe allergic reaction of rapid onset affecting many body systems.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] It is due to the release of inflammatory mediators and cytokines from mast cells and basophils, typically due to an immunologic reaction but sometimes with non-immunologic mechanisms.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Interleukin (IL)–4 and IL-13 are cytokines important in the initial generation of antibody and inflammatory cell responses to anaphylaxis.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] The vast majority of anaphylaxis is mediated by allergen-specific immunoglobulin E (IgE).
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] In the immunologic mechanism, immunoglobulin E (IgE) binds to the antigen (the foreign material that provokes the allergic reaction).
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Antigen-bound IgE then activates FcεRI receptors on mast cells and basophils.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] This leads to the release of inflammatory mediators such as histamine.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] These mediators subsequently increase the contraction of bronchial smooth muscles, trigger vasodilation, increase the leakage of fluid from blood vessels, and compromise circulatory function.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Rarely, anaphylaxis may be triggered by immunoglobulin G (IgG) antibodies.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Non-immunologic mechanisms involve substances that directly cause the degranulation of mast cells and basophils without ligating the high-affinity IgE receptor.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] These include agents such as contrast medium, opioids, temperature (hot or cold), and vibration.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Sulfites may cause reactions by both immunologic and non-immunologic mechanisms.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] This is a form of pseudoallergy and is commonly mediated by MRPRX2, a promiscuous receptor that interacts with many substances (especially drugs) to trigger mast cell degranulation without IgE.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] A form of anaphylaxis that has both IgE-dependent and non-IgE-dependent features has been observed as a consequence of some chemotherapy and monoclonal antibodies, manifesting alongside cytokine storm-like features.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Anaphylaxis is diagnosed on the basis of a person's signs and symptoms.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Two or more of the following symptoms after a likely contact with an allergen: a.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Skin involvement may include: hives, itchiness, or a swollen tongue, among others.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Respiratory difficulties may include: shortness of breath, stridor, or low oxygen levels, among others.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Low blood pressure is defined as a greater than 30% decrease from a person's usual blood pressure.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] In adults, a systolic blood pressure of less than 90 mmHg is often used.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] During an attack, blood tests for tryptase or histamine (released from mast cells) might be useful in diagnosing anaphylaxis due to insect stings or medications.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] However these tests are of limited use if the cause is food or if the person has a normal blood pressure, and they are not specific for the diagnosis.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] To ensure that an elevated tryptase is not the result of hereditary alpha tryptasemia, the EAACI recommends repeating a tryptase level 24 hours after resolution of anaphylaxis.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Additionally, a normal tryptase does not rule out anaphylaxis.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] There are three main classifications of anaphylaxis.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] **Biphasic anaphylaxis** is the recurrence of symptoms within 1–72 hours after resolution of an initial anaphylactic episode.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Estimates of incidence vary between less than 1% and up to 20% of cases.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] The recurrence typically occurs within 8 hours.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] It is managed in the same manner as anaphylaxis.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] **Anaphylactoid reaction**, **non-immune anaphylaxis**, or **pseudoanaphylaxis**, is a type of anaphylaxis that does not involve an allergic reaction but is due to direct mast cell degranulation.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Non-immune anaphylaxis is the current term, as of 2018, used by the World Allergy Organization with some recommending that the old terminology, "anaphylactoid", no longer be used.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Allergy testing may help in determining the trigger.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Skin allergy testing is available for certain foods and venoms.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Blood testing for specific IgE can be useful to confirm milk, egg, peanut, tree nut, and fish allergies.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Skin testing is available to confirm penicillin allergies, but is not available for other medications.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Non-immune forms of anaphylaxis can only be determined by history or exposure to the allergen in question, and not by skin or blood testing.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] It can sometimes be difficult to distinguish anaphylaxis from asthma, syncope, and panic attacks.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Asthma however typically does not entail itching or gastrointestinal symptoms, syncope presents with pallor rather than a rash, and a panic attack may have flushing but does not have hives.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Other conditions that may present similarly include: scrombroidosis and anisakiasis.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] In a person who died from anaphylaxis, autopsy may show an "empty heart" attributed to reduced venous return from vasodilation and redistribution of intravascular volume from the central to the peripheral compartment.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Other signs are laryngeal edema, eosinophilia in lungs, heart and tissues, and evidence of myocardial hypoperfusion.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Laboratory findings could detect increased levels of serum tryptase, an increase in total and specific IgE serum levels.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Avoidance of the trigger of anaphylaxis is recommended.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] In cases where this may not be possible, desensitization may be an option.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Immunotherapy with Hymenoptera venoms is effective at desensitizing 80–90% of adults and 98% of children against allergies to bees, wasps, hornets, yellowjackets, and fire ants.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Oral immunotherapy may be effective at desensitizing some people to certain food including milk, eggs, nuts and peanuts; however, adverse effects are common.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] For example, many people develop an itchy throat, cough, or lip swelling during immunotherapy.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Desensitization is also possible for many medications, however it is usually advised that most people simply avoid the agent in question.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] In those who react to latex it may be important to avoid cross-reactive foods such as avocados, bananas, and potatoes among others.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Premedications with antihistamines or glucocorticoids does not prevent anaphylaxis, but may be used in specific circumstances, such as rush aeroallergen desensitization or in certain chemotherapy regimens.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Anaphylaxis is a medical emergency that may require resuscitation measures such as airway management, supplemental oxygen, large volumes of intravenous fluids, and close monitoring.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Passive leg raise may also be helpful in the emergency management.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Administration of intravenous fluid bolus and epinephrine is the treatment of choice with antihistamines used as adjuncts.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] A period of in-hospital observation for between 2 and 24 hours is recommended for people once they have returned to normal due to concerns of biphasic anaphylaxis.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Epinephrine (adrenaline) (1:1000) is the primary treatment for anaphylaxis with no absolute contraindication to its use.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] It is recommended that an epinephrine solution be given intramuscularly into the mid anterolateral thigh as soon as the diagnosis is suspected.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] The injection may be repeated every 5 to 15 minutes if there is insufficient response.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] A second dose is needed in 16–35% of episodes with more than two doses rarely required.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] The intramuscular route is preferred over subcutaneous administration because the latter may have delayed absorption.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] It is recommended that after diagnosis and treatment of anaphylaxis, the patient should be kept under observation in an appropriate clinical setting until symptoms have fully resolved.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Minor adverse effects from epinephrine include tremors, anxiety, headaches, and palpitations.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] People on β-blockers may be resistant to the effects of epinephrine, but this is less of an issue with "cardioselective" β1-blockers.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] In this situation, if epinephrine is not effective, intravenous glucagon can be administered, which has a mechanism of action independent of β-receptors.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] If necessary, it can also be given intravenously using a dilute epinephrine solution.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Intravenous epinephrine, however, has been associated both with dysrhythmia and myocardial infarction.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Epinephrine autoinjectors used for self-administration typically come in two doses, one for adults or children who weigh more than 25 kg and one for children who weigh 10 to 25 kg.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Most recently, the FDA has approved an intranasal form of epinephrine under the brand name Neffy, on the basis of its ability to attain levels of epinephrine in people that are believed to be protective against anaphylaxis.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] There are currently no clinical data on its effectiveness.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Delayed administration of epinephrine in anaphylaxis is associated with increased rates of hospitalization and mortality.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Antihistamines (both H1 and H2), while commonly used and assumed effective based on theoretical reasoning, are poorly supported by evidence.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] A 2007 Cochrane review did not find any good-quality studies upon which to base recommendations and they are not believed to affect airway edema or spasm.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Corticosteroids are unlikely to make a difference in the current episode of anaphylaxis, but may be used in the hope of decreasing the risk of biphasic anaphylaxis.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Their prophylactic effectiveness in these situations is uncertain.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Nebulized salbutamol may be effective for bronchospasm that does not resolve with epinephrine.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Methylene blue has been used in those not responsive to other measures due to its presumed effect of relaxing smooth muscle.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] People prone to anaphylaxis are advised to have an allergy action plan.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Parents are advised to inform schools of their children's allergies and what to do in case of an anaphylactic emergency.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] The action plan usually includes use of epinephrine autoinjectors, the recommendation to wear a medical alert bracelet, and counseling on avoidance of triggers.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Immunotherapy is available for certain triggers to prevent future episodes of anaphylaxis.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] A multi-year course of subcutaneous desensitization has been found effective against stinging insects, while oral desensitization is effective for many foods.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] In those in whom the cause is known and prompt treatment is available, the prognosis is good.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Even if the cause is unknown, if appropriate preventive medication is available, the prognosis is generally good.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Usually, death occurs due to either respiratory failure (typically involving asphyxia) or cardiovascular complications, such as cardiovascular shock, with 0.7–20% of cases causing death.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] There have been cases of death occurring within minutes.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Outcomes in those with exercise-induced anaphylaxis are typically good, with fewer and less severe episodes as people get older.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] The number of people who get anaphylaxis is 4–100 per 100,000 persons per year, with a lifetime risk of 0.05–2%.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] About 30% of affected people get more than one attack.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Exercise-induced anaphylaxis affects about 1 in 2000 young people.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Rates appear to be increasing: the numbers in the 1980s were approximately 20 per 100,000 per year, while in the 1990s, it was 50 per 100,000 per year.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] The increase appears to be primarily for food-induced anaphylaxis.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] The risk is greatest in young people and females.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Anaphylaxis leads to as many as 500–1,000 deaths per year (2.7 per million) in the United States, 20 deaths per year in the United Kingdom (0.33 per million), and 15 deaths per year in Australia (0.64 per million).
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Another estimate from the United States puts the death rate at 0.7 per million.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Mortality rates have decreased between the 1970s and 2000s.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] In Australia, death from food-induced anaphylaxis occur primarily in women while deaths due to insect bites primarily occur in males.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Death from anaphylaxis is most commonly triggered by medications.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] The conditions of anaphylaxis have been known since ancient times.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] French physician François Magendie had described how rabbits were killed by repeated injections of egg albumin in 1839.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] However, the phenomenon was discovered by two French physiologists Charles Richet and Paul Portier.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] In 1901, Albert I, Prince of Monaco requested Richet and Portier join him on a scientific expedition around the French coast of the Atlantic Ocean, specifically to study on the toxin produced by cnidarians (like jellyfish and sea anemones).
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Richet and Portier boarded Albert's ship *Princesse Alice II* for ocean exploration to make collections of the marine animals.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Richet and Portier extracted a toxin called hypnotoxin from their collection of jellyfish (but the real source was later identified as Portuguese man o' war) and sea anemone (*Actinia sulcata*).
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] In their first experiment on the ship, they injected a dog with the toxin in an attempt to immunise the dog, which instead developed a severe reaction (hypersensitivity).
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] In 1902, they repeated the injections in their laboratory and found that dogs normally tolerated the toxin at the first injection, but on re-exposure, three weeks later with the same dose, they always developed fatal shock.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] They also found that the effect was not related to the doses of toxin used, as even small amounts in secondary injections were lethal.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Thus, instead of inducing tolerance (prophylaxis), which they expected, they discovered effects of the toxin as deadly.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] In 1902, Richet introduced the term *aphylaxis* to describe the condition of lack of protection.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] He later changed the term to *anaphylaxis* on the grounds of euphony.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] The term is from the Greek ἀνά-, *ana-*, meaning "against", and φύλαξις, *phylaxis*, meaning "protection".
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] On 15 February 1902, Richet and Portier jointly presented their findings before the *Societé de Biologie* in Paris.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] The moment is regarded as the birth of allergy (the term invented by Clemens von Pirquet in 1906) study (allergology).
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Richet continued to study the phenomenon and was eventually awarded the Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine for his work on anaphylaxis in 1913.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] There are ongoing efforts to develop sublingual epinephrine to treat anaphylaxis.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Trials of sublingual epinephrine, currently called AQST-108 (dipivefrin) and sponsored by Aquestive Therapeutics, are in phase 1 trials as of December 2021.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Subcutaneous injection of the anti-IgE antibody omalizumab is being studied as a method of preventing recurrence, but it is not yet recommended.
[src:cereal-germ/anaphylaxis] Omalizumab-associated anaphylaxis has been observed in less than 0.1% of patients treated for moderate to severe persistent allergic asthma using subcutaneous omalizumab injections.
[src:cereal-germ/andrew-weil] Weil was born in Philadelphia, on June 8, 1942, the only child of parents who operated a millinery store, in a family that was Reform Jewish.
[src:cereal-germ/andrew-weil] He graduated from Central High School (Philadelphia) in 1959, and was awarded a scholarship from the American Association for the United Nations, giving him the opportunity to go abroad for a year, during which he lived with families in India, Thailand, and Greece.
[src:cereal-germ/andrew-weil] From this experience, he became convinced that American culture and science was insular and unaware of non-American practices.
[src:cereal-germ/andrew-weil] He began hearing that mescaline enhanced creativity and produced visionary experiences, and finding little information on the subject, he read *The Doors of Perception* by Aldous Huxley.
[src:cereal-germ/andrew-weil] In 1960, Weil entered Harvard University, where he majored in biology with a concentration in ethnobotany.
[src:cereal-germ/andrew-weil] At Harvard, he developed curiosity about psychoactive drugs.
[src:cereal-germ/andrew-weil] He met Harvard psychologists Timothy Leary and Richard Alpert, and separately engaged in organized experimentation with mescaline.
[src:cereal-germ/andrew-weil] and that this reporting included the claim that "undergraduates had indeed been able to obtain access to psilocybin from members" of the Harvard faculty research team that was involved in such research.
[src:cereal-germ/andrew-weil] Weil's undergraduate thesis was titled "The Use of Nutmeg as a Psychotropic Agent," specifically, on the narcotic properties of nutmeg, chair of the Department of Social Relations, and a former director of Harvard's Center for Research in Personality.
[src:cereal-germ/andrew-weil] In 1964, he graduated *cum laude* with a B.A. in biology.
[src:cereal-germ/andrew-weil] Weil moved to San Francisco and completed a one-year medical internship at Mount Zion Hospital in 1968–69.
[src:cereal-germ/andrew-weil] While there, he volunteered at the Haight-Ashbury Free Clinic.
[src:cereal-germ/andrew-weil] Weil is reported to have experienced opposition to this line of inquiry at the NIMH, to have departed to his rural northern Virginia home (1971-1972), and to have begun his practices of vegetarianism, yoga, and meditation, and work on writing *The Natural Mind* (1972).
[src:cereal-germ/andrew-weil] In 1994, Weil founded the Arizona Center for Integrative Medicine at the University of Arizona College of Medicine in Tucson, Arizona.
[src:cereal-germ/andrew-weil] Andrew Weil is the founder of True Food Kitchen, a restaurant chain serving meals on the premise that food should make one feel better.
[src:cereal-germ/andrew-weil] There are currently 44 restaurants in the chain.
[src:cereal-germ/andrew-weil] Weil is credited with popularizing the 4-7-8 breathing technique.
[src:cereal-germ/andrew-weil] Evidence-based medicine is a stated central component of the higher-order "system of systems" Weil envisions integrative medicine to be.
[src:cereal-germ/andrew-weil] It is clear that in both scholarly/academic and popular settings, Weil's statements suggest practices from alternative therapies as being something to add to conventional medical treatment plans.
[src:cereal-germ/andrew-weil] However, Weil is also on record speaking disparagingly of conventional, evidence-based medicine, both in academic and popular contexts.
[src:cereal-germ/andrew-weil] Weil acknowledges many experiences and individuals that have influenced his philosophical and spiritual ideas, and the techniques he considers valid in his approach to medicine.
[src:cereal-germ/andrew-weil] Weil has been open about his own history of experimental and recreational drug use, including experiences with narcotics and mind-altering substances.
[src:cereal-germ/andrew-weil] Among the individuals who strongly influenced his personal and professional life is the late osteopath Robert C.
[src:cereal-germ/andrew-weil] Fulford, who specialized in cranial manipulation.
[src:cereal-germ/andrew-weil] Weil has further stated that he respects the work of psychologist Martin Seligman, who pioneered the field of positive psychology and now directs the Positive Psychology Center at the University of Pennsylvania.
[src:cereal-germ/andrew-weil] Weil has also professed admiration for the work of Stephen Ilardi, professor of psychology at the University of Kansas, and author of *The Depression Cure*.
[src:cereal-germ/andrew-weil] In particular, he is a proponent of diets that are rich in organic fruits, organic vegetables, and fish, and is a vocal critic of foods and diets rich in partially hydrogenated oils.
[src:cereal-germ/andrew-weil] In an interview on *Larry King Live*, Weil focused on a view that sugar, starch, refined carbohydrates, and trans-fats are more dangerous to the human body than saturated fats.
[src:cereal-germ/andrew-weil] Regarding treatment strategies, their side effects, and their efficacy, Weil advocates for the use of whole plants as a less problematic approach in comparison to synthetic pharmaceuticals.
[src:cereal-germ/andrew-weil] In addition, Weil is an advocate of incorporating specific medicinal mushrooms into one's diet.
[src:cereal-germ/andrew-weil] Weil has expressed opposition to the war on drugs, and takes a measured, nuanced approach to the use of recreational drugs.
[src:cereal-germ/andrew-weil] While Weil's early books and publications primarily explored altered states of consciousness, he has since expanded the scope of his work to encompass healthy lifestyles and health care in general.
[src:cereal-germ/andrew-weil] In the last ten years, Weil has focused much of his work on the health concerns of older people.
[src:cereal-germ/andrew-weil] In his book *Healthy Aging*, Weil looks at the process of growing older from a physical, social, and cross-cultural perspective, and in his book *Why our Health Matters* is focused on health care reform.
[src:cereal-germ/andrew-weil] As of 2015, Weil was serving as series editor of an academic imprint from Oxford University Press called the *Weil Integrative Medicine Library*, volumes for clinicians in more than 10 medical specialties, including oncology, cardiology, rheumatology, pediatrics, and psychology.
[src:cereal-germ/andrew-weil] Weil co-edited the first volume, *Integrative Oncology*, with Donald Abrams, which appeared in 2009.
[src:cereal-germ/andrew-weil] Academic and scholarly reviews of the series and individual volumes were lacking as of 2015—in almost all cases, the publisher's "Reviews and Awards" tabs lack society or other published reviews (apart from Doody's).
[src:cereal-germ/andrew-weil] Weil was a regular contributor to *High Times* magazine from 1975 to 1983.
[src:cereal-germ/andrew-weil] More recently, Weil has written the forewords to a variety of books, including Paul Stamets's *Psilocybin Mushrooms of the World* and Lewis Mehl-Madrona's *Coyote Medicine*.
[src:cereal-germ/andrew-weil] In the 21st century, Weil has occasionally written articles for *Time* magazine.
[src:cereal-germ/andrew-weil] Medical professionals in particular have criticized Weil for promoting treatment claims and alternative medicine practices described as unverified or inefficacious, or for otherwise rejecting aspects of evidence-based medicine.
[src:cereal-germ/andrew-weil] Weil's rejection of some aspects of evidence-based medicine and his promotion of alternative medicine practices that are not verifiably efficacious were criticized in a 1998 *New Republic* piece by Arnold S.
[src:cereal-germ/andrew-weil] Relman, emeritus editor-in-chief of The New England Journal of Medicine and emeritus professor of medicine at Harvard Medical School.
[src:cereal-germ/andrew-weil] Weil appeared on the cover of *Time* magazine in 1997 and again in 2005, and *Time* named him one of the 25 most influential Americans in 1997 and one of the 100 most influential people in the world in 2005.
[src:cereal-germ/andrew-weil] He was inducted into the Academy of Achievement in 1998.
[src:cereal-germ/andrew-weil] Weil blogs for the *Huffington Post* and has been a frequent guest on *Larry King Live* on CNN, *Oprah*, and *The Today Show*.
[src:cereal-germ/andrew-weil] Weil appeared in the 2012 documentary on the need for a "rescue" of American healthcare, *Escape Fire*.
[src:cereal-germ/andrew-weil] He also appeared in the 2019 documentary *Fantastic Fungi*.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] These nervous-system dysfunctions occur in several different patterns, with different results and different possible causes.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] Ataxia can be limited to one side of the body, which is referred to as **hemiataxia.** Friedreich's ataxia has gait abnormality as the most commonly presented symptom.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] **Dystaxia** is a mild degree of ataxia.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] The term cerebellar ataxia is used to indicate ataxia due to dysfunction of the cerebellum.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] The cerebellum is responsible for integrating a significant amount of neural information that is used to coordinate smoothly ongoing movements and to participate in motor planning.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] Although ataxia is not present with all cerebellar lesions, many conditions affecting the cerebellum do produce ataxia.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] People with cerebellar ataxia may have trouble regulating the force, range, direction, velocity, and rhythm of muscle contractions.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] This results in a characteristic type of irregular, uncoordinated movement that can manifest itself in many possible ways, such as asthenia, asynergy, delayed reaction time, and dyschronometria.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] Individuals with cerebellar ataxia could also display instability of gait, difficulty with eye movements, dysarthria, dysphagia, hypotonia, dysmetria, and dysdiadochokinesia.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] These deficits can vary depending on which cerebellar structures have been damaged, and whether the lesion is bi- or unilateral.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] People with cerebellar ataxia may initially present with poor balance, which could be demonstrated as an inability to stand on one leg or perform tandem gait.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] As the condition progresses, walking is characterized by a widened base and high stepping, as well as staggering and lurching from side to side.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] Turning is also problematic and could result in falls.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] As cerebellar ataxia becomes severe, great assistance and effort are needed to stand and walk.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] Dysarthria, an impairment with articulation, may also be present and is characterized by "scanning" speech that consists of a slower rate, irregular rhythm, and variable volume.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] Also, slurring of speech, tremor of the voice, and ataxic respiration may occur.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] Cerebellar ataxia could result in incoordination of movement, particularly in the extremities.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] Overshooting (or hypermetria) occurs with finger-to-nose testing and heel-to-shin testing; thus, dysmetria is evident.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] Impairments with alternating movements (dysdiadochokinesia), as well as dysrhythmia, may also be displayed.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] Tremor of the head and trunk (titubation) may be seen in individuals with cerebellar ataxia.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] Dysmetria is thought to be caused by a deficit in the control of interaction torques in multijoint motion.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] Interaction torques are created at an associated joint when the primary joint is moved.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] For example, if a movement required reaching to touch a target in front of the body, flexion at the shoulder would create a torque at the elbow, while extension of the elbow would create a torque at the wrist.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] These torques increase as the speed of movement increases and must be compensated for and adjusted to create coordinated movement.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] This may, therefore, explain decreased coordination at higher movement velocities and accelerations.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] The term sensory ataxia is used to indicate ataxia due to loss of proprioception, the loss of sensitivity to the positions of joint and body parts.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] This is generally caused by dysfunction of the dorsal columns of the spinal cord, because they carry proprioceptive information up to the brain.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] In some cases, the cause of sensory ataxia may instead be dysfunction of the various parts of the brain that receive positional information, including the cerebellum, thalamus, and parietal lobes.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] Sensory ataxia presents itself with an unsteady "stomping" gait with heavy heel strikes, as well as a postural instability that is usually worsened when the lack of proprioceptive input cannot be compensated for by visual input, such as in poorly lit environments.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] Physicians can find evidence of sensory ataxia during physical examination by having patients stand with their feet together and eyes shut.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] In affected patients, this will cause the instability to worsen markedly, producing wide oscillations and possibly a fall; this is called a positive Romberg's test.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] Worsening of the finger-pointing test with the eyes closed is another feature of sensory ataxia.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] Also, when patients are standing with arms and hands extended toward the physician, if the eyes are closed, the patients' fingers tend to "fall down" and then be restored to the horizontal extended position by sudden muscular contractions (the "ataxic hand").
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] The term vestibular ataxia is used to indicate ataxia due to dysfunction of the vestibular system, which in acute and unilateral cases is associated with prominent vertigo, nausea, and vomiting.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] In slow-onset, chronic bilateral cases of vestibular dysfunction, these characteristic manifestations may be absent, and dysequilibrium may be the sole presentation.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] The three types of ataxia have overlapping causes, so they can either coexist or occur in isolation.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] Cerebellar ataxia can have many causes despite normal neuroimaging.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] Exogenous substances that cause ataxia mainly do so because they have a depressant effect on central nervous system function.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] The most common example is ethanol (alcohol), which is capable of causing reversible cerebellar and vestibular ataxia.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] Chronic intake of ethanol causes atrophy of the cerebellum by oxidative and endoplasmic reticulum stresses induced by thiamine deficiency.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] A further class of pharmaceuticals which can cause short-term ataxia, especially in high doses, are benzodiazepines.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] Exposure to high levels of methylmercury, through consumption of fish with high mercury concentrations, is also a known cause of ataxia and other neurological disorders.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] Ataxia can be induced as a result of severe acute radiation poisoning with an absorbed dose of more than 30 grays.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] Furthermore, those with ataxia telangiectasia may have a high sensitivity towards gamma rays and x-rays.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] Vitamin B12 deficiency may cause, among several neurological abnormalities, overlapping cerebellar and sensory ataxia.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] Neuropsychological symptoms may include sense loss, difficulty in proprioception, poor balance, loss of sensation in the feet, changes in reflexes, dementia, and psychosis, which can be reversible with treatment.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] Complications may include a neurological complex known as subacute combined degeneration of spinal cord, and other neurological disorders.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] Symptoms of neurological dysfunction may be the presenting feature in some patients with hypothyroidism.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] These include reversible cerebellar ataxia, dementia, peripheral neuropathy, psychosis and coma.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] Most of the neurological complications improve completely after thyroid hormone replacement therapy.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] Peripheral neuropathies may cause generalised or localised sensory ataxia (e.g., a limb only) depending on the extent of the neuropathic involvement.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] Spinal disorders of various types may cause sensory ataxia from the lesioned level below, when they involve the dorsal columns.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] Non-hereditary causes of cerebellar degeneration include chronic alcohol use disorder, head injury, paraneoplastic and non-paraneoplastic autoimmune ataxia, high-altitude cerebral edema, celiac disease, normal-pressure hydrocephalus, and infectious or post-infectious cerebellitis.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] Ataxia may depend on hereditary disorders consisting of degeneration of the cerebellum or of the spine; most cases feature both to some extent, and therefore present with overlapping cerebellar and sensory ataxia, even though one is often more evident than the other.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] An example of X-linked ataxic condition is the rare fragile X-associated tremor/ataxia syndrome or FXTAS.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] Arnold–Chiari malformation is a malformation of the brain.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] It consists of a downward displacement of the cerebellar tonsils and the medulla through the foramen magnum, sometimes causing hydrocephalus as a result of obstruction of cerebrospinal fluid outflow.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] Succinic semialdehyde dehydrogenase deficiency is an autosomal-recessive gene disorder where mutations in the ALDH5A1 gene results in the accumulation of gamma-Hydroxybutyric acid (GHB) in the body.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] GHB accumulates in the nervous system and can cause ataxia as well as other neurological dysfunction.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] Wilson's disease is an autosomal-recessive gene disorder whereby an alteration of the ATP7B gene results in an inability to properly excrete copper from the body.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] Copper accumulates in the liver and raises the toxicity levels in the nervous system causing demyelination of the nerves.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] This can cause ataxia as well as other neurological and organ impairments.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] Gluten ataxia is an autoimmune disease, which is triggered by the ingestion of gluten.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] Early diagnosis and treatment with a gluten-free diet can improve ataxia and prevent its progression.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] The effectiveness of the treatment depends on the elapsed time from the onset of the ataxia until diagnosis, because the death of neurons in the cerebellum as a result of gluten exposure is irreversible.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] It accounts for 40% of ataxias of unknown origin and 15% of all ataxias.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] Less than 10% of people with gluten ataxia present any gastrointestinal symptom and only about 40% have intestinal damage.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] It *can* co-occur with celiac disease and some maintain it is a presentation thereof.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] However, gluten ataxia is believed to be mediated by transglutaminase 6 antibodies, whereas celiac disease is associated with transglutaminase 2 antibodies.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] There is a continuum between presymptomatic ataxia and immune ataxias with clinical deficits.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] Gluten ataxia is classified as a primary auto-immune cerebellar ataxia (PACA).
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] Malfunction of the sodium-potassium pump may be a factor in some ataxias.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] The Na+/K+ pump has been shown to control and set the intrinsic activity mode of cerebellar Purkinje neurons.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] This suggests that the pump might not simply be a homeostatic, "housekeeping" molecule for ionic gradients, but could be a computational element in the cerebellum and the brain.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] Indeed, a ouabain block of Na+/K+ pumps in the cerebellum of a live mouse results in it displaying ataxia and dystonia.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] Ataxia is observed for lower ouabain concentrations, and dystonia is observed at higher ouabain concentrations.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] Antibodies against the enzyme glutamic acid decarboxylase (GAD: enzyme changing glutamate into GABA) cause cerebellar deficits.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] The antibodies impair motor learning and cause behavioral deficits.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] GAD antibodies related ataxia is part of the group called immune-mediated cerebellar ataxias.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] The cerebellum is particularly vulnerable to autoimmune disorders.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] Cerebellar circuitry has capacities to compensate and restore function thanks to cerebellar reserve, gathering multiple forms of plasticity.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] LTDpathies gather immune disorders targeting long-term depression (LTD), a form of plasticity.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] The treatment of ataxia and its effectiveness depend on the underlying cause.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] Treatment may limit or reduce the effects of ataxia, but it is unlikely to eliminate them entirely.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] Recovery tends to be better in individuals with a single focal injury (such as stroke or a benign tumour), compared to those who have a neurological degenerative condition.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] A review of the management of degenerative ataxia was published in 2009.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] A small number of rare conditions presenting with prominent cerebellar ataxia are amenable to specific treatment, and recognition of these disorders is critical.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] Diseases include vitamin E deficiency, abetalipoproteinemia, cerebrotendinous xanthomatosis, Niemann–Pick type C disease, Refsum's disease, glucose transporter type 1 deficiency, episodic ataxia type 2, gluten ataxia, glutamic acid decarboxylase ataxia.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] Novel therapies target the RNA defects associated with cerebellar disorders, using in particular anti-sense oligonucleotides.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] The movement disorders associated with ataxia can be managed by pharmacological treatments and through physical therapy and occupational therapy to reduce disability.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] Physical therapy requires a focus on adapting activity and facilitating motor learning for retraining specific functional motor patterns.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] A recent systematic review suggested that physical therapy is effective, but there is only moderate evidence to support this conclusion.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] Current research suggests that, if a person can walk with or without a mobility aid, physical therapy should include an exercise program addressing five components: static balance, dynamic balance, trunk-limb coordination, stairs, and contracture prevention.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] Once the physical therapist determines that the individual can safely perform parts of the program independently, it is important that the individual be prescribed and regularly engage in a supplementary home exercise program that incorporates these components to improve long-term outcomes further.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] These outcomes include balance tasks, gait, and individual activities of daily living.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] While the improvements are attributed primarily to changes in the brain and not just the hip or ankle joints, it is still unknown whether the improvements are due to adaptations in the cerebellum or compensation by other areas of the brain.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] Decomposition, simplification, or slowing of multijoint movement may also be an effective strategy that therapists may use to improve function in patients with ataxia.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] Training likely needs to be intense and focused—as indicated by one study performed with stroke patients experiencing limb ataxia who underwent intensive upper limb retraining.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] Their therapy consisted of constraint-induced movement therapy which resulted in improvements of their arm function.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] Treatment should likely include strategies to manage difficulties with everyday activities such as walking.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] Gait aids (such as a cane or walker) can be provided to decrease the risk of falls associated with impairment of balance or poor coordination.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] Severe ataxia may eventually lead to the need for a wheelchair.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] To obtain better results, possible coexisting motor deficits need to be addressed in addition to those induced by ataxia.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] For example, muscle weakness and decreased endurance could lead to increased fatigue and poorer movement patterns.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] Several assessment tools are available to therapists and healthcare professionals working with patients with ataxia.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] The International Cooperative Ataxia Rating Scale (ICARS) is one of the most widely used and has been proven to have very high reliability and validity.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] Other tools that assess motor function, balance and coordination are also highly valuable to help the therapist track the progress of their patient, as well as to quantify the patient's functionality.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] The term "ataxia" is sometimes used in a broader sense to indicate a lack of coordination in some physiological process.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] Examples include **optic ataxia** (lack of coordination between visual inputs and hand movements, resulting in inability to reach and grab objects) and ataxic respiration (lack of coordination in respiratory movements, usually due to dysfunction of the respiratory centres in the medulla oblongata).
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] Optic ataxia may be caused by lesions to the posterior parietal cortex, which is responsible for combining and expressing positional information and relating it to movement.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] Outputs of the posterior parietal cortex include the spinal cord, brain stem motor pathways, pre-motor and pre-frontal cortex, basal ganglia, and the cerebellum.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] Some neurons in the posterior parietal cortex are modulated by intention.
[src:cereal-germ/ataxia] Optic ataxia is usually part of Balint's syndrome, but can be seen in isolation with injuries to the superior parietal lobule, as it represents a disconnection between the visual-association cortex and the frontal premotor and motor cortex.
[src:cereal-germ/awb-limited] The AWB was founded in 1939 to regulate the wheat market after the excesses of the Great Depression.
[src:cereal-germ/awb-limited] This type of arrangement was not unique to Australia, as the Canadian Wheat Board was created in 1935 in a similar fashion (but its history dates back to an earlier wheat marketing board created during World War I, and also includes the experience of cooperative wheat pools during the 1920s).
[src:cereal-germ/awb-limited] For much of its early history, it was a government-run and owned company.
[src:cereal-germ/awb-limited] In July 1999, it was restructured as a private company.
[src:cereal-germ/awb-limited] It offered "class A" shares to those who met its definition of growers and who had the ability to elect the majority of its board and chairperson, and from August 2001, 'class B' were publicly traded on the Australian Securities Exchange.
[src:cereal-germ/awb-limited] In 2008, constitutional amendments were passed.
[src:cereal-germ/awb-limited] Despite resistance from several wheat lobbies and industry groups, it consolidated ownership of AWB into one type of share, giving growers no special consideration.
[src:cereal-germ/awb-limited] This change was proposed by the AWB management as necessarily to having a simpler, lower-risk business model.
[src:cereal-germ/awb-limited] After privatisation, AWB grew to incorporate a number of subsidiaries to diversify its income away from its wheat exports.
[src:cereal-germ/awb-limited] Its subsidiary businesses include GrainFlow to manage collection of grain from farmers to ports, companies to ship the grain overseas to customers, and Landmark rural services.
[src:cereal-germ/awb-limited] AWB Limited was a holding company owning a number of subsidiaries.
[src:cereal-germ/awb-limited] Its shares were freely traded on the Australian Securities Exchange.
[src:cereal-germ/awb-limited] AWB Limited had a number of subsidiaries.
[src:cereal-germ/awb-limited] Some of these subsidiaries existed due to legislative requirements relating to the operation of the single desk; others exist for the purpose of controlling credit risk.
[src:cereal-germ/awb-limited] AWB announced a new strategy in 2009 to simplify and de-risk the business.
[src:cereal-germ/awb-limited] This resulted in the divestment of the financial services loan book to the ANZ Bank in December 2009.
[src:cereal-germ/awb-limited] In March 2010, AWB announced the signing of a memorandum of understanding to sell the Geneva business and to joint venture the local grain trading business.
[src:cereal-germ/awb-limited] Previously a low profile organisation, the AWB made headlines in late 2005 when it was alleged that it had knowingly paid kickbacks to the Iraq Government, in violation of United Nations sanctions and Australian law.
[src:cereal-germ/awb-limited] Following the Iraqi invasion of Kuwait in 1990, the United Nations had imposed a financial and trade embargo on Iraq.
[src:cereal-germ/awb-limited] However, after facing criticism over the humanitarian impacts of the sanctions, the UN from 1995 until late 2003 allowed Iraq to trade oil on the world market in exchange for food, medicine and other humanitarian needs.
[src:cereal-germ/awb-limited] Despite this, at the insistence of the Iraq government of dictator Saddam Hussein, the AWB agreed to pay "transportation fees" of around $A$290 million.
[src:cereal-germ/awb-limited] This money was paid to a Jordanian transportation company, Alia.
[src:cereal-germ/awb-limited] Alia kept a small percentage of the fees, and paid the remainder onto Saddam's government.
[src:cereal-germ/awb-limited] This breached the sanctions placed on the Iraqi regime.
[src:cereal-germ/awb-limited] The government-sanctioned Cole Inquiry into the company's role in the scandal has been completed and was tabled by Attorney-General Philip Ruddock on 27 November 2006.
[src:cereal-germ/awb-limited] The report found that, from mid-1999, AWB had knowingly entered into an arrangement that involved paying kickbacks to the Iraqi government, in order to retain its business.
[src:cereal-germ/awb-limited] The Inquiry recommended that 12 people be investigated for possible criminal and corporations offences over the scandal.
[src:cereal-germ/awb-limited] At the height of the investigation, the single-desk arrangement from which AWB benefits came under criticism.
[src:cereal-germ/awb-limited] In 2006, the Australian Grain Exporters Association asked the Government to remove AWB's monopoly export powers.
[src:cereal-germ/awb-limited] The oil-for-wheat scandal cast doubt among some grain exporters over the trust placed in the company, especially as they lost the ability to export to Iraq during the length of the Cole Inquiry, losing one of their biggest markets.
[src:cereal-germ/awb-limited] The scandal resulted in international condemnation and litigation.
[src:cereal-germ/awb-limited] On 11 July 2006, North American farmers claimed $1 billion in damages from AWB at Washington DC, alleging the Australian wheat exporter used bribery and other corrupt activities to corner grain markets.
[src:cereal-germ/awb-limited] The growers claimed that AWB used the same techniques to secure grain sales in other markets in Asia and other countries in the Middle East.
[src:cereal-germ/awb-limited] The lawsuit was dismissed in March 2007.
[src:cereal-germ/awb-limited] In August 2009, the Australian Federal Police dropped their investigation into any criminal actions undertaken by AWB and others in this matter.
[src:cereal-germ/awb-limited] This decision came after Paul Hastings QC declared the prospect of convictions was limited and "not in the public interest".
[src:cereal-germ/awb-limited] The Australian Securities & Investments Commission then proceeded with several civil cases against six former directors and officers of AWB.
[src:cereal-germ/awb-limited] AWB's former managing director Andrew Lindberg and former chief financial officer Paul Ingleby were ultimately fined and banned from managing a company for one year.
[src:cereal-germ/awb-limited] Former chairman Trevor Flugge was also fined, and banned from managing a company for five years.
[src:cereal-germ/awb-limited] A civil suit brought by shareholders of AWB was settled out of court for $39.5 million in February 2010.
[src:cereal-germ/awb-limited] Australia's government has distanced itself from the payments to Saddam Hussein's regime, given Australia's contribution to military action against Hussein in the 2003 invasion of Iraq.
[src:cereal-germ/awb-limited] Andrew Lindberg resigned as managing director on 9 February 2006 and from the board of directors on 22 February 2006 under intense public and media pressure.
[src:cereal-germ/awb-limited] In the years immediately following the Cole Inquiry, AWB continued to be dogged by bad performance.
[src:cereal-germ/awb-limited] Following the publication of the Cole Inquiry, a new management team was installed under the leadership of Gordon Davis who was recruited from Orica in August 2006.
[src:cereal-germ/awb-limited] Davis successfully reformed the constitution and the shareholder structure to consolidate into 1 class of shareholder.
[src:cereal-germ/awb-limited] This new management team has not been entirely without controversy.
[src:cereal-germ/awb-limited] On 26 April 2007, Yahoo News reported that AWB also breached US sanctions on Iran.
[src:cereal-germ/awb-limited] These sanctions prohibit American citizens and companies using American currency from trading with Iran.
[src:cereal-germ/awb-limited] In 2006, AWB's US subsidiary attempted to pay an Iranian transport company approximately $1 million, in clear breach of the US sanctions.
[src:cereal-germ/awb-limited] In 2009, the company faced difficulties in another new market, when it was forced to recapitalise the balance sheet after the company produced significant losses from the expansion of trading activities into Brazil under Davis.
[src:cereal-germ/awb-limited] Despite making a small profit in 2009, in March 2010, the company announced a profit downgrade from domestic trading activities.
[src:cereal-germ/awb-limited] In May 2010, it reported a half-year loss of $64.8 million, which it claimed due to the cost of settling the shareholder class action for $39.5m, and a loss of $65.4m on restructuring costs associated with its sale of the Landmark Financial Services loan and deposit books.
[src:cereal-germ/awb-limited] In July 2010, AWB entered into an agreement to merge with GrainCorp.
[src:cereal-germ/awb-limited] This did not proceed, after Agrium made a successful takeover offer that was completed in December 2010, with the company delisted from the Australian Securities Exchange.
[src:cereal-germ/awb-limited] In 2011, Cargill acquired the AWB Commodity Management business from Agrium.
[src:cereal-germ/cereal-germ] The **germ** of a cereal grain is the part that develops into a plant; it is the seed embryo.
[src:cereal-germ/cereal-germ] Along with bran, germ is often a by-product of the milling that produces refined grain products.
[src:cereal-germ/cereal-germ] Cereal grains and their components, such as wheat germ oil, rice bran oil, and maize bran, may be used as a source from which vegetable oil is extracted, or used directly as a food ingredient.
[src:cereal-germ/cereal-germ] The germ is retained as an integral part of whole-grain foods.
[src:cereal-germ/cereal-germ] Non-whole grain methods of milling are intended to isolate the endosperm, which is ground into flour, with removal of both the husk (bran) and the germ.
[src:cereal-germ/cereal-germ] Removal of bran produces a flour with a white rather than a brown color and eliminates fiber.
[src:cereal-germ/cereal-germ] The germ is rich in polyunsaturated fats (which have a tendency to oxidize and become rancid on storage) and so germ removal improves the storage qualities of flour.
[src:cereal-germ/cereal-germ] Wheat germ or wheatgerm is a concentrated source of several essential nutrients, including vitamin E, folate (folic acid), phosphorus, thiamin, zinc, and magnesium, as well as essential fatty acids and fatty alcohols.
[src:cereal-germ/cereal-germ] White bread is made using flour that has had the germ and bran removed.
[src:cereal-germ/cereal-germ] Wheat germ can be added to protein shakes, casseroles, muffins, pancakes, cereals, yogurt, smoothies, cookies, and other goods.
[src:cereal-germ/cereal-germ] Wheat germ can become rancid if not properly stored in a refrigerator or freezer and away from sunlight.
[src:cereal-germ/cereal-germ] Some manufacturers prevent rancidity by storing wheat germ in vacuum-sealed glass containers, or by placing an oxygen-absorbing sachet inside air-tight packaging.
[src:cereal-germ/cereal-germ] In molecular biology, wheat germ extract is used to carry out cell-free *in vitro* translation experiments: the plant embryo contains all the macromolecular components necessary for translating mRNA into proteins, but relatively low levels of its own mRNA.
[src:cereal-germ/cereal-germ] Wheat germ is also useful in biochemistry since it contains lectins that bind strongly to certain glycoproteins; therefore, it can be used to isolate such proteins.
